rComments: Interesting orator. Articulate, but sometimes has nothing to say (but says it anyway). Selected reading material is fantastic though, if a little self-indulgent. You will probably enjoy this class in some capacity but don't expect to simply pass. You will need to earn it.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Professor Gibbs is an incredible lecturer, and highly intelligent philosopher.  His insight draws you in and makes even the most mundane topics interesting.  However, he does grade tough; he expects good philosophy too.
Why University? Philosophy and the University- interesting class, very easy and stress-free way to raise my GPA

Intelligent, entertaining, diverse, funny ~ a dedicated professor. One of the fairest marking schemes at U of T. Review the readings several times for clarity and don't miss class (not that you'd want to!). Hope to be a member of his classroom ASAP.
Good professor. Gibbs clearly knows his Continental philosophy and is a great expositor of extremely difficult texts. If you apply yourself to the readings, you'll get a lot out of his lectures.

Not being maudlin here but Gibbs changed my life. Broke down my whole way of being and built it up again -leaving a little room for the unknown and the possibility of this metamorphosis happening again - the most intuitively brilliant man I've ever known

Prof. Gibbs is one of the best things about attending the U of T. Inspirational. Any student with any inclination toward the humanities should make a point of a taking a course with him purely for the sake of seeing difficult materials illuminated.
An excellent professor! One of the best I've had!
Passionate about his area (cont. philosoph), a great communicator.
